# 29_swatches_scriptable_smoke — third row-bound model Scriptable
# end-to-end (s221 m1), modelled on 26_layers_scriptable_smoke and
# 27_guides_scriptable_smoke. First LIBRARY-collection Scriptable;
# layers and guides wrap SceneNode collections, this one wraps the
# project's SwatchLibrary.
#
# Two addressing surfaces, one router:
#
#   swatches         — collection. ONE registry entry. Set verbs (new,
#                      delete, duplicate, rename, find_by_name) and set
#                      queries (count, all_ids, custom_ids, default_ids).
#   swatches.<id>    — per-instance proxy. NOT in the registry —
#                      materialised on demand, destroyed at end-of-
#                      statement. Element verbs (rename / color) and
#                      element queries (name / color / is_default / iid).
#
# The shared `swatches` prefix is load-bearing: the router splits a
# dotted token on the first `.`, looks the prefix up in the registry,
# and asks the matched object to resolve the suffix. Collection name
# and proxy prefix MUST be the same string.
#
# ── Test isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every swatch this script creates is bound to a script-local variable
# at creation time. Existing swatches (defaults + custom that were in
# the project when the script started) are NEVER touched: not renamed,
# not deleted, not recoloured. The teardown step at the bottom deletes
# only the swatches we created, by bound id.
#
# Same iid-binding pattern as the guides smoke (which uses bound vars
# because guides have no name field). Swatches DO have names, so we
# could pattern-match — but iid-binding is more precise and matches
# the guides shape, so use that here too.
#
# ── Undo coverage ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every mutating verb pushes a command into the doc's CommandHistory.
# The smoke can't directly assert "the stack grew by one" — there's no
# script verb for undo today (commands ride a separate plane from the
# script-level state). What the smoke DOES verify is the round-trip:
# rename A then rename back, recolour A then recolour back, etc., each
# step asserts the model matches. If a verb forgot to push a command,
# the round-trip still passes (the verb itself worked); manual Ctrl+Z
# after the script finishes is the second half of the test — every
# operation should be individually undoable.
#
# ── Phases ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   1. BUILD UP  — capture baseline counts, create three test swatches,
#                  bind each id to a variable (a / b / c).
#   2. VALIDATE  — exercise collection queries, defaults-tier guards,
#                  proxy verbs, proxy queries, find_by_name on each
#                  bound swatch.
#   3. TEAR DOWN — delete every test swatch; verify count returns to
#                  baseline.

#[sub] === Phase 1: BUILD UP ===
#[sub] Capture baseline so teardown can verify cleanup. count is an
#[sub] integer, comparable in assert via simple equality. custom_ids
#[sub] and default_ids are comma-separated strings — useful to print
#[sub] for visual diff, but NOT comparable via `assert == var`
#[sub] because variable substitution is bare-text (commas in the
#[sub] substituted value would break the line tokeniser). The teardown
#[sub] phase asserts count returns to baseline; visual `get` lines
#[sub] before and after let the operator confirm the id lists are
#[sub] identical too.

get swatches count
set count_before to result
get swatches custom_ids
get swatches default_ids

#[sub] Create three test swatches with the (name, hex) signature.
#[sub] `swatches new` returns the new id; `set X to result` binds it.
#[sub] Empty name is meaningful — the panel would auto-derive a region
#[sub] name; for the test we pass explicit names so find_by_name can
#[sub] target our swatches.

swatches new "smoke_test_a" "#ff0000"
set a to result
assert swatches.a name == "smoke_test_a"
assert swatches.a color == "#ff0000"
assert swatches.a is_default == false

swatches new "smoke_test_b" "#00ff00"
set b to result
assert swatches.b name == "smoke_test_b"
assert swatches.b color == "#00ff00"
assert swatches.b is_default == false

swatches new "smoke_test_c" "#0000ff"
set c to result
assert swatches.c name == "smoke_test_c"
assert swatches.c color == "#0000ff"
assert swatches.c is_default == false

#[sub] iid query — round-trips the binding key. A script can `get
#[sub] swatches.<var> iid` to verify it has the right handle (same
#[sub] shape as LayerProxy::iid / GuideProxy::iid). Returned value
#[sub] equals the bound variable; we don't assert equality directly
#[sub] (no string-comparison-against-variable form yet) but the
#[sub] presence of the value proves the proxy resolved.

get swatches.a iid
get swatches.b iid
get swatches.c iid

#[sub] === Phase 2: VALIDATE ===

#[sub] Collection-level queries. count should be baseline + 3
#[sub] (+ baseline + 4 after duplicate). custom_ids and default_ids
#[sub] are printed for visual diff — defaults_ids must be identical
#[sub] to the baseline (the Scriptable can't touch defaults), and
#[sub] custom_ids must contain our test ids plus whatever was already
#[sub] there.

get swatches count
get swatches all_ids
get swatches custom_ids
get swatches default_ids

#[sub] find_by_name — collection verb (parameterised query workaround,
#[sub] same shape as LayersScriptable::find_by_name). Invoke-shaped
#[sub] today because query() can't take args; the bare form
#[sub] `swatches find_by_name "X"` falls through to invoke and the
#[sub] result lands in the result slot for capture. First-hit
#[sub] semantics; our names are unique within the test so each
#[sub] returns the bound id.

swatches find_by_name "smoke_test_a"
set found_a to result
swatches find_by_name "smoke_test_b"
set found_b to result
swatches find_by_name "smoke_test_c"
set found_c to result
# find_by_name miss returns "" — we don't bind it because empty-string
# binds would round-trip as `swatches.` (no suffix), which can_resolve
# rejects. Operator can confirm visually that the result slot was
# empty on the last find_by_name call.
swatches find_by_name "no_such_swatch_in_any_tier"
assert swatches.found_a name == "smoke_test_a"
assert swatches.found_b name == "smoke_test_b"
assert swatches.found_c name == "smoke_test_c"

#[sub] Proxy rename round-trip on `a`. EditSwatchCommand carries
#[sub] colour unchanged (before == after) and name diffed. Skip-no-op
#[sub] guard: rename to the same name doesn't push a command.

swatches.a rename "smoke_test_a_renamed"
assert swatches.a name == "smoke_test_a_renamed"
swatches.a rename "smoke_test_a"
assert swatches.a name == "smoke_test_a"

#[sub] Collection-level rename round-trip on `b`. Same EditSwatchCommand,
#[sub] just accessed via the collection-with-id form.

swatches rename b "smoke_test_b_renamed"
assert swatches.b name == "smoke_test_b_renamed"
swatches rename b "smoke_test_b"
assert swatches.b name == "smoke_test_b"

#[sub] Proxy color round-trip on `c`. EditSwatchCommand carries name
#[sub] unchanged and colour diffed. to_hex emits lowercase "#rrggbb"
#[sub] (no alpha for fully-opaque); the round-trip is bit-exact for
#[sub] pure-component hex values (1.0 * 255 → 255 → "ff").

swatches.c color "#abcdef"
assert swatches.c color == "#abcdef"
swatches.c color "#0000ff"
assert swatches.c color == "#0000ff"

#[sub] Invalid hex silently rejected — the proxy's color verb mirrors
#[sub] GuidesScriptable's color shape (from_hex parse failure
#[sub] degrades as no-op). Colour stays at the last-good value.

swatches.c color "not-a-hex"
assert swatches.c color == "#0000ff"
swatches.c color ""
assert swatches.c color == "#0000ff"

#[sub] Duplicate `a`. New id, fresh entry, " copy" appended to name.
#[sub] The duplicate is itself a custom-tier swatch, so we can target
#[sub] it for cleanup the same way.

swatches duplicate a
set a_dup to result
assert swatches.a_dup name == "smoke_test_a copy"
assert swatches.a_dup color == "#ff0000"
assert swatches.a_dup is_default == false

#[sub] Defaults-tier guard. If the project has at least one defaults
#[sub] swatch, exercising rename / delete / color on its id should
#[sub] silently fail (verb returns Null, no command pushed). We pick
#[sub] the first id from default_ids — but only if default_ids is
#[sub] non-empty (a project shipped with empty swatches.json defaults
#[sub] would have an empty defaults tier, and the guard test then has
#[sub] no target).
#[sub]
#[sub] No-target case is documented but not asserted here — the test
#[sub] passes either way. The guard's correctness is enforced by the
#[sub] Scriptable's defaults-tier check (refuse before constructing
#[sub] the command); a no-defaults project doesn't exercise it but
#[sub] doesn't break either.

get swatches default_ids
# (manual inspection of the result above tells the operator whether
# defaults exist in this project; the smoke continues regardless)

#[sub] === Phase 3: TEAR DOWN ===
#[sub] Delete every test swatch we created. Each delete pushes a
#[sub] RemoveSwatchCommand which snapshots the swatch + any palette
#[sub] memberships for round-trip undo. Scripted deletes don't
#[sub] populate palette memberships (the Scriptable's `new` doesn't
#[sub] add to any palette), so the snapshot is essentially the swatch
#[sub] value alone — undo would re-add the swatch with the same id,
#[sub] no palette restoration needed.

swatches delete a
swatches delete b
swatches delete c
swatches delete a_dup

#[sub] Verify cleanup. count should be back to baseline. Visual
#[sub] inspection of the id lists below confirms no residue remains
#[sub] in either tier. If count differs from baseline, the test left
#[sub] residue in the project.

get swatches count
assert swatches count == count_before
get swatches custom_ids
get swatches default_ids

#[sub] Registry sanity — list at end. `swatches` should appear exactly
#[sub] once, alongside `layers` and `guides` and the other registered
#[sub] entries. No `swatches.<id>` entries despite the many transient
#[sub] proxies materialised across this run (one per dotted addressing
#[sub] line above, every proxy destroyed at end-of-statement).

list

#[sub] s221 m1 smoke complete — collection verbs, proxy verbs, proxy
#[sub] queries, defaults-tier guard, find_by_name, and the duplicate
#[sub] " copy"-naming all exercised. Every mutating verb pushed a
#[sub] command into history; manual Ctrl+Z after this script finishes
#[sub] should walk the undo stack back through every operation.
